              <td class="py-3 pr-4"><span class="text-xs px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full bg-emerald-500/10 text-emerald-500 font-medium">CC-BY 4.0</span></td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-center">Yes</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-center">Yes</td>
              <td class="py-3 text-center">Yes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Academic papers</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4"><span class="text-xs px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full bg-emerald-500/10 text-emerald-500 font-medium">CC-BY 4.0</span></td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-center">Yes</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-center">Yes</td>
              <td class="py-3 text-center">Yes</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="glass rounded-lg p-4 mt-8">
      <p class="text-xs text-[var(--color-text-faint)] leading-relaxed">
        <strong class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">Why two licenses?</strong>
        Apache 2.0 includes a patent grant that CC-BY lacks â€” critical for anyone integrating TARA into
        compliance tooling or medical device software. CC-BY 4.0 is the academic standard for open-access
        research and what repositories like Zenodo and arXiv expect. Both require only attribution. Neither
        restricts commercial use.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p class="mt-12 text-xs text-[var(--color-text-faint)]">
      Copyright 2024-2026 Kevin Qi / Qinnovate.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageLayout>
